---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The Automations Guide is written by Ian Chamberland, a RevOps practitioner who has built automation workflows for real GTM and revenue operations teams."
>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="about-hero">
      <p class="section-label">About this site</p>
      <h1>Built by a RevOps practitioner, for RevOps practitioners.</h1>
      <p style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.75;max-width:580px;margin-top:1rem;">
        Ian Chamberland here. I've spent years working inside GTM and revenue operations teams —
        building the automations, wiring up the tools, and inheriting the messes that happen when
        stacks grow faster than processes do.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-content">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Why this site exists</h2>
        <p>
          Most automation content online is written by people who have never actually had to
          maintain a workflow in production, deal with a Zapier task limit at 11pm before a
          campaign goes live, or explain to a VP of Sales why their lead routing broke.
        </p>
        <p>
          I built this site to be the resource I wish existed when I was figuring out which
          tools to buy, which workflows to build first, and which vendor claims to ignore.
          Everything here comes from direct experience — not from reading documentation or
          regurgitating feature lists.
        </p>

        <h2>What I cover</h2>
        <p>
          The Automations Guide focuses on the automation layer that sits underneath modern
          revenue operations: the middleware, the CRM workflows, the data plumbing that
          makes GTM motions run (or not run) smoothly.
        </p>

        <h3>Specifically:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Automation platform comparisons — Zapier, Make, n8n, and where each one actually breaks</li>
          <li>HubSpot and Salesforce workflow automation, including the edge cases the docs skip</li>
          <li>Sales-to-CS handoff automation and the handoff failure modes I've personally shipped</li>
          <li>Lead routing, scoring, and enrichment workflows using Clay, Apollo, and HubSpot</li>
          <li>RevOps tech stack decisions — what to buy, what to skip, what order to build in</li>
          <li>AI-assisted automation in GTM contexts, including what's actually useful vs. hype</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How I work</h2>
        <p>
          I only write about tools I've used in a real environment. That means I've paid for
          them, hit their limits, submitted support tickets, and migrated off them when something
          better came along. The write-ups here reflect that — including when a tool is genuinely
          good, when it's overpriced for what it does, and when I'd recommend starting with the
          free tier indefinitely.
        </p>
        <p>
          I don't recommend tools based on commission size. If a tool has a better affiliate rate
          but is the wrong call for most RevOps teams, I won't push it. The only tools that get
          a "try this" recommendation here are ones I have personally evaluated and would use
          (or have used) in a real stack.
        </p>

        <h2>Affiliate Disclosure</h2>
        <p>
          Some links on this site are affiliate links. When you sign up for or purchase a tool
          through one of those links, I may earn a commission at no extra cost to you. Affiliate
          relationships are disclosed on pages where they exist. My editorial take is never
          influenced by whether an affiliate program is available — some of the tools I recommend
          most frequently have no affiliate program at all.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you have questions about anything I've written or want to suggest a topic, you can
          reach me at <a href="mailto:ian@theautomationsguide.com">ian@theautomationsguide.com</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
